@genderlogindia @japna_p @asmitaghosh18 @ladkidyutiful @Haiyya_Act @RupsaMallik @SwarnsB @PSYfem @siputriwidi @sachp Working with abuse survivors is always challenging. Self care is often forgotten and I keep slipping into depression and anxiety. I guess for people like us, it should be a habit but it’s not. I need to step it up.

@genderlogindia @japna_p @asmitaghosh18 @ladkidyutiful @Haiyya_Act @RupsaMallik @SwarnsB @PSYfem @siputriwidi @sachp When I first started working in the area, I started with my own story of being a CSA and suicide survivor. Most of my family didn’t like it. It hurt that they couldn’t stand with me at that moment of reclamation. But then, there were others who support continually.

@genderlogindia @japna_p @asmitaghosh18 @ladkidyutiful @Haiyya_Act @RupsaMallik @SwarnsB @PSYfem @siputriwidi @sachp That kind of hurts. So while I encourage people to break stereotypes, I have to struggle breaking some in my head. Regaining control over my sexuality and redefining it post divorce vis a vis my work and traditional upbringing is another stressor.

@genderlogindia @japna_p @asmitaghosh18 @ladkidyutiful @Haiyya_Act @RupsaMallik @SwarnsB @PSYfem @siputriwidi @sachp My stressors are always related to explaining my work to a traditional Muslim family. Sexuality is taboo in our families and I feel anxious when my work comes up. May have to do with internalised conditioning but I also realise I’m not the ‘good girl’ of the khaandaan anymore.
